The “treble sceptres” carried by Banquo’s descendants could be a reference to King James and the three
sceptres he received during his coronations. This connection implies that, like King James, Banquo’s
descendants are the rightful heirs to the throne. Macbeth is later referred to as “bloodysceptered”, which
contrasts with Banquo’s descendants and suggests that Macbeth’s violent actions make him an unworthy ruler.
